Staff writer
Aaron ‘Smith thinks a lot of people

stay away from art because they are L

intimidated by it.

“I think there’s this idea out there
that art can’t be done, that it is something
outside of ourselves,” he said.

But Smith, who is the resident direc-
tor of Schenley Quad, said he feels that

exposing students to art will make them

more comfortable with it —-—- and, he
hopes, more eager to explore it.
That is the idea behind the Arts in

the Residence Halls program that Smith .

directs. It is a program that brings differ-
ent kinds of art into the dorms to make it
more accessible to students.

The sixth instalhnent of the program
was held in McCormick Hall last night
with a combination poetry reading and
art exhibit. Smith worked with sopho-
more Matthew‘ Novak and freshman
Elizabeth Pearson to organize the event,
which drew more than 50 students.
Some read their poetry aloud while oth-
ers chose to listen. Several student artists
also showed off their works of painting
and sculpting. A .

There was art to appeal to the ears as
well as the eyes. Pitt student Phil Boyd
entertained the group with music from
his guitar and harmonica. He played two
songs, “Cramps in Your Foot” and
“Black-Clad Country Love,” both of
which he wrote.

Recently, the Provost’s Office began
to give ﬁnancial support to the event,

allowing the organizers to offer prize
money to’ the winning artists. The $50
first prize went to poet Matt Wilson.
Margot Douaihy and Phil Boyd each
won one of the two $25 second prizes.

Karen Themstrup, one of the judges,
enthusiastically said she was impressed
with Mike Romani, Matt Wilson and all
the other poets who read.

“This is amazing,” she said. “I’m
really encouraged by the level of creativ-
ity and artistic expression these students
are showing.”

Themstrup, a painter and poet, is an

'M.F.A. student of poetry and instructor

of the Introduction to Poetry class. She
has read her own work at
Hemmingway’s and Barnes and Noble,
and has shown her paintings at the South
Side Gallery Women’s Work.

Smith eagerly agreed with
Themstrup’s critique of the event.

“This is incredible,” he said. “The
event is blowing me away. The students’
enthusiasm to express themselves and
the quality of that expression is amaz-
mg.”

Past events have offered students the
opportunity to meet several well-known
poets. Irene McKinney, the poet laureate
of West Virginia, and Toi Derricotte, a
widely published poet and instructor at
Pitt, have made appearances.

Poet Margot Douaihy called the
event a “gift to the students.”

“I give so much credit to the school
and the RAs for giving us the chance to

see the talents of other students,” she 

said.

