Bill Clinton might have rrrade a big mistake
last Friday when he claimed executive privilege for
two of his aides — Bruce Lindsey and Sidney
Blumenthal — to protect them from having to tes-
tify in the Paula Jones proceedings.

Executive privilege is an optionafforded the
president so he can protect information which, if it
were released, would seriously cripple the adminis-
tration. The Supreme Court aﬁirmed this right pro-
visionally in 1974, even while in the process of
denying it to Richard Nixon, who wished to use
executive privilege to keep his audio recordings
private. ,

If the current case makes it to the Supreme
Court, the court will most likely not deny the priv-
ilege to President Clinton, ‘as the case under inves-
tigation does not seem so serious as to warrant an
overriding the privilege.

The Watergate case was about a president who
was alleged to have employed several departments
of the federal government — including the FBI and
CIA — to obstruct a very serious criminal investi-
gation. The Paula Jones case is a civil dispute con-
cerning a far lesser oﬁense, and those who enjoy
comparing the two scandals should remember this
diﬁerence. . ,

But the fact ﬂrat Clinton was charged with a
lesser crime makes it all the more puzzling that he
would claim executive privilege now. The worst
thing his aides might say, if they were put on the
stand, is that he told them about some extramarital
affair of his, or that maybe one of them passed a
note to an intern in a hallway. And most of the pub-
he no longer seems to care about the case (as evi-
denced by the fact that the article about executive
privilege was buried 11 pages into The New York
Times.)

The only end this move served was to make
Clinton look guilty. And the White House advisers
who have criticized Republican leaders for saying
just this have just rrrade the adnrinistration look
even more foolish. Republicans may very well be
engaging in partisan politics, but they are still just
stating the obvious.

Executive privilege can be a court-aﬂirmed
method of obstructing justice (or rather, obstructing
an investigation, if the obstruction itself seems just).
But for Clinton to have exercised it cannot help him
inacasewheretheveryquestionathandiswhether
he has obstructed justice in the past.

